WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.300 --> 00:00:02.300
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Hi everybody.

00:00:02.300 --> 00:00:06.890
We are joined today by Chef Marcus Samuelsson;
he is the chef and owner of Red Rooster in

00:00:06.890 --> 00:00:10.330
Harlem in
New York City, the winner of Top Chef Masters,

00:00:10.330 --> 00:00:14.990
and the author of "Yes, Chef," a memoir chronicling
his extraordinary journey from

00:00:14.990 --> 00:00:20.570
Ethiopia to Sweden to Harlem, with many stops
along the way including the White House.

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:23.109
There is a line from "Yes, Chef"--
&gt;&gt;Marcus: And the Google office.

00:00:23.109 --> 00:00:24.880
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: And the Google office most
importantly.

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:25.880
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Yes.

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:27.140
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: On 14th Street.

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:30.800
There's a line in "Yes, Chef" that struck
me that I wanted to read: "Who’s going to

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:33.440
make the
people realize that food dismissed as ‘ethnic’

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:37.399
by the fine-dining world could be produced
at the same level as their sacred

00:00:37.399 --> 00:00:42.289
bouillabaisses and veloutés?” and I have
to say, after reading "Yes, Chef" the answer

00:00:42.289 --> 00:00:43.460
is Chef Marcus Samuelsson.

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:47.309
So please me in
welcoming to Google New York, Marcus Samuelsson.

00:00:47.309 --> 00:00:48.309
[Applause]

00:00:48.309 --> 00:00:49.309
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Thank you.

00:00:49.309 --> 00:00:50.309
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Glad you're here.

00:00:50.309 --> 00:00:51.309
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Thank you.

00:00:51.309 --> 00:00:52.920
I'm happy to be back.

00:00:52.920 --> 00:01:00.570
I've been here twice, one time for the launch
of the African book, "The Soul of a New

00:01:00.570 --> 00:01:04.780
Cuisine," and one time with Martha Stewart
for a Christmas thing you guys were doing.

00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:06.860
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: And this is the best time--third
time's the best, right?

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:08.400
&gt;&gt;Marcus: It is, by far.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.400
By far.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:10.400
[Laughter]

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:13.680
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: So I have to admit I read your
book and reading it made me feel like possibly

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:19.070
the laziest human being on the planet
because you have done everything and worked

00:01:19.070 --> 00:01:22.990
so hard throughout your career--your quite
long career at this point because you

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:24.500
started quite young.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:29.380
And I can't even imagine--you're only forty-one
now--which is very young by my standards because

00:01:29.380 --> 00:01:32.180
I'm not quite
forty yet--but I can't even imagine what you're

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:36.410
going to do in the next ten or twenty years--so
what made this moment the right

00:01:36.410 --> 00:01:37.730
moment to write a memoir?

00:01:37.730 --> 00:01:45.520
&gt;&gt;Marcus: I think that there's an evolution
right, as a self and as a chef and I always

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:50.200
actually envisioned to be a good chef by
forty-two or something like that because I

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:55.630
think that's a perfect age in terms of you
know who you are and being a chef, so

00:01:55.630 --> 00:02:01.190
much about it is knowing who you are, and
you can express that through food.

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:05.440
But also where I was in my life, you know,
married; I

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:13.570
knew about my Ethiopian side; I also knew
where in the DNA, in terms of my restaurant,

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:15.030
where do I need to be?

00:02:15.030 --> 00:02:19.440
Where was it important
for me to be, beside just having a store?

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:24.200
And all of that takes time; it takes time
to become a good chef, not that many become

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:30.180
good chefs, you have to find the conscious
of finding yourself; and then, where do you

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:31.780
need to operate from?

00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:37.830
You know, I became
chef very early--maybe too early--but then

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:43.030
also hadn't asked myself those questions of
"Is there something larger?

00:02:43.030 --> 00:02:46.870
Can I be part of
changing the footprint in this city?

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:50.790
What's going on in the food chasm in this
specific city, in this country?

00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:51.850
What are my
responsibilities?"

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:52.910
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That's great.

00:02:52.910 --> 00:02:56.730
Well, you know, the book is so beautifully
written and, just starting with the first

00:02:56.730 --> 00:02:59.280
chapter I have
to admit it actually almost brought me to

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:03.010
tears reading about--the story about your
mother and how you've never seen a picture

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:05.950
of
your birth mother and that vignette was really

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:07.600
a very powerful story--

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:08.600
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Yeah.

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:11.069
&gt;&gt;Interviewer:--And one that I think a lot
of people didn't know about you, if they know

00:03:11.069 --> 00:03:13.050
some parts of your life.

00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:16.100
Was--when you
read the final manuscript--was there a story

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:20.960
or an event that struck you as particularly
poignant and important to write about?

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:25.470
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well, I think I want to keep a book
that has the pace of myself.

00:03:25.470 --> 00:03:28.650
I mean the chapters are pretty short, so there's
a fast

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:30.030
good pace, it's a quick read.

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:33.460
If you're an immigrant like me, it might take
two weeks, but someone like you who's been

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:34.540
here longer
maybe two days.

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:40.849
[claps hands together] It's a quick, I wanted
to keep a quick read, and also have people

00:03:40.849 --> 00:03:43.540
from all walks of life
share it at a dinner table.

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:48.450
If you were seventeen and wanted to--was into
cooking--you could read this book and relate

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:49.450
to it.

00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:53.590
If you were the parent, you could sort of
like see yourself in your journey and your

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:58.080
struggles; and if you were the grandparent,
there was this sort of "Oh, that's what we

00:03:58.080 --> 00:03:59.200
do with our kids.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:00.200
We inspire them to cook."

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:05.410
So keeping the pace but also keeping it an
entry level to all people.

00:04:05.410 --> 00:04:13.680
You know for me it's important to explain
the journey in terms of profession, specifically,

00:04:13.680 --> 00:04:17.039
cheffing is
so different today than it was when I came

00:04:17.039 --> 00:04:18.039
in, right?

00:04:18.039 --> 00:04:22.300
It was one way, you worked in a French restaurant,
and you worked yourself,

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:28.169
you know, as hard as possible, and the only
way to respond was "yes, chef."

00:04:28.169 --> 00:04:32.059
But, just as much as your business evolved,
ours too.

00:04:32.059 --> 00:04:37.159
So now people might know cooking through Top
Chef or through an online recipe.

00:04:37.159 --> 00:04:38.159
What happened?

00:04:38.159 --> 00:04:39.159
What was the difference?

00:04:39.159 --> 00:04:42.159
I wanted to
explain that sort of--that journey and also

00:04:42.159 --> 00:04:49.229
explain for people from all colors a window
in to how a black laborer's journey is,

00:04:49.229 --> 00:04:50.759
because it is different.

00:04:50.759 --> 00:04:53.259
Just like a woman's journey is different.

00:04:53.259 --> 00:04:56.210
And guys can always say like, "No no it doesn't
matter, there's no

00:04:56.210 --> 00:04:57.210
difference.

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:58.210
We're all open."

00:04:58.210 --> 00:04:59.210
It is different.

00:04:59.210 --> 00:05:03.981
And it's not about an [author] conversation
about race that wasn't polarizing.

00:05:03.981 --> 00:05:06.020
It's
like "You know what, I've never thought about

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:11.639
that" and from all sides of it say like "You
know what, that's uh, hmm.

00:05:11.639 --> 00:05:12.650
I've never thought about that journey."

00:05:12.650 --> 00:05:16.289
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Let's talk a little bit about
that because you do talk a lot about race

00:05:16.289 --> 00:05:22.159
in the book and it's a really fascinating
perspective being one of--really the only--executive

00:05:22.159 --> 00:05:26.039
chefs of color in the city, I mean maybe {Chef
Cardo Stenza} there's maybe a handful

00:05:26.039 --> 00:05:28.060
in sort of the fine dining arena--

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:29.060
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Mmm

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:32.589
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: But you've really made a mark
for yourself and you write a lot about the

00:05:32.589 --> 00:05:35.189
racism that you've faced along the way in
your career,

00:05:35.189 --> 00:05:38.789
some of the really off color remarks that
were made to you by quite prominent chefs

00:05:38.789 --> 00:05:40.879
that were really disturbing to me and made
me

00:05:40.879 --> 00:05:44.719
not want to watch certain programs ever again,
it just--there've been a lot of challenges

00:05:44.719 --> 00:05:49.659
that you've faced and what about those
experiences sort of influenced the way you

00:05:49.659 --> 00:05:50.659
run your business now?

00:05:50.659 --> 00:05:54.719
&gt;&gt;Marcus: I think that I've been lucky enough
to work in really great restaurants and that

00:05:54.719 --> 00:05:58.529
taught me what to do, but also taught me
what not to do more than anything.

00:05:58.529 --> 00:06:04.129
If I walked into any great French restaurant
that I worked in, there was no women, zero.

00:06:04.129 --> 00:06:07.080
It
was--the narrative of the black chef didn't

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:13.229
exist to the point where you had to explain
for them that you were there working in the

00:06:13.229 --> 00:06:17.970
kitchen many, many, many times and even when
I got the job, they didn't have the job because

00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:23.560
it was a black chef, so that does two
things--that either makes you sharper or quit.

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:27.650
And a lot of people quit and that's their
life answer why you don't have

00:06:27.650 --> 00:06:30.710
more diverse entry level in the work force.

00:06:30.710 --> 00:06:34.129
And cooking is just one thing, you can say
the same in the tech world, you can say the

00:06:34.129 --> 00:06:37.779
same in--I mean, the book is a mirror up--
to look introvert yourself-- to look into

00:06:37.779 --> 00:06:39.099
yourself, "You know what?

00:06:39.099 --> 00:06:41.740
How does that reflect
MY environment?"

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:42.770
You know?

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:48.080
And I mean the fact that there's not enough
women in the cooking world is just nonsense

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:50.479
because the
most influential people in cooking have always

00:06:50.479 --> 00:06:51.479
been women.

00:06:51.479 --> 00:06:52.479
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Sure.

00:06:52.479 --> 00:06:56.069
&gt;&gt;Marcus: You can look at it from just eating
around the world, but you can also look at

00:06:56.069 --> 00:06:59.199
it from in this country who changed the
game?

00:06:59.199 --> 00:07:02.610
Alice Waters and Julia Childs.

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:05.639
We wouldn't have Food TV without Julia.

00:07:05.639 --> 00:07:08.199
We wouldn't think--we have fifty-four farmer's
markets in

00:07:08.199 --> 00:07:09.589
New York City.

00:07:09.589 --> 00:07:14.159
Without Alice asking those questions, maybe
we'd have two.

00:07:14.159 --> 00:07:17.289
On the larger scale, who are the biggest game
changers?

00:07:17.289 --> 00:07:18.460
Women.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:23.270
And just that cooking in terms of a restaurant,
in terms of fine dining, which is one segment

00:07:23.270 --> 00:07:28.529
of this conversation, could be
argued that it's more suitable for a guy.

00:07:28.529 --> 00:07:35.779
It's almost like an Olympic--you run really
really fast but that does not explain what,

00:07:35.779 --> 00:07:39.659
who contribute our community and changes how
we eat.

00:07:39.659 --> 00:07:44.080
Fine dining cooking is the minority in this
pyramid that we call food--food

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:45.379
community.

00:07:45.379 --> 00:07:51.330
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Well talking about your journey
some more you've had--excuse me, I think I

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:54.509
alluded to this in the introduction--many
many along

00:07:54.509 --> 00:07:58.649
this journey and I would love to hear more
about that journey including your time almost

00:07:58.649 --> 00:08:03.020
becoming a professional soccer player to
cooking for the White House and some of the

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:04.490
key moments that stand out for you.

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:06.289
If you can just tell us a little bit about
them.

00:08:06.289 --> 00:08:10.830
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well for me one of the key moments
ever was when I was allowed to work for free

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:12.449
for a year.

00:08:12.449 --> 00:08:14.059
When I got the chance to work in France.

00:08:14.059 --> 00:08:19.800
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: We would hire you for that
for a year, if you wanted to work for free

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:20.800
here.

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:21.800
[laughter]

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:22.800
Just kind of ignoring me--we would pay--

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:23.839
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well, you know--it would be a good
education for both, I'll tell you that.

00:08:23.839 --> 00:08:27.020
We'd be closing the gap on the food chasm,
I'll

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:28.469
tell you that.

00:08:28.469 --> 00:08:32.180
I would ask a lot of questions and you guys
are smarter than me so you would fix it.

00:08:32.180 --> 00:08:33.180
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: We'd just Google it.

00:08:33.180 --> 00:08:34.180
[laughter] And find the answer.

00:08:34.180 --> 00:08:35.180
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Yeah, exactly.

00:08:35.180 --> 00:08:42.659
No but that chance to work in the three star
Michelin Restaurant in France was for me a

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.750
big success because
I sent out thirty-five letters.

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:49.960
Me and my mother went to the local library
to send out a lot of letters and we got just

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:51.800
like a--I
think that the undertone in the book should

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:54.800
be about rejection--how do you deal with rejection?

00:08:54.800 --> 00:08:58.630
All of us here have been rejected
and how do you deal with that?

00:08:58.630 --> 00:09:05.360
It's in the personal life, it is--it happens
in work place and what you do with that?

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:09.900
And for me it
was actually the perfect time.

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:15.269
You know, I started writing to three star
Michelin Restaurants when I was eighteen-nineteen-twenty

00:09:15.269 --> 00:09:16.839
but I didn't get there until I was twenty-three.

00:09:16.839 --> 00:09:21.779
But it actually turned out to be better for
me because I was a better cook.

00:09:21.779 --> 00:09:25.100
Although each one of those answers back were
painful.

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:30.250
But in the meantime I taught myself French
and I was a better cook.

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:33.040
So the
rejection does not always have to be that

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:38.450
you have to get off your journey, you know,
I went to Switzerland instead of France, and

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:43.510
they spoke French in Switzerland and German
so now I got yelled at in Swedish, German

00:09:43.510 --> 00:09:47.620
and French, which was a good advantage
because before I went to France, I need to

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:49.120
know some of that.

00:09:49.120 --> 00:09:53.459
So it's being committed to the craft, being
completely in love with

00:09:53.459 --> 00:09:55.560
your craft.

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:59.770
If there was anyway I doubted that, there
was no way I would have taken that abuse,

00:09:59.770 --> 00:10:02.379
or those things.

00:10:02.379 --> 00:10:05.899
I'm also now
thinking about is there a way to create incredible

00:10:05.899 --> 00:10:07.020
food without abuse?

00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:08.140
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: What's the answer?

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.959
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well, we're searching.

00:10:11.959 --> 00:10:17.300
[laughter] Because there is a commitment inside
that you can't doubt that has to happen and

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:21.410
I
think, you know, I think Red Rooster's asked

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:23.950
me a lot of questions and I have to answer
them.

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:29.899
I always trust my work and I seek new
questions in my work.

00:10:29.899 --> 00:10:35.110
And you know, I've been lucky enough on the
book tour to travel to some of the best restaurants

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:38.839
in the ci--in
the country and I ask--you know I get a window

00:10:38.839 --> 00:10:43.050
in to what's going on in American food and
it's a better plate today.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:47.250
It's more
diverse whether you eat in Chinese, Muslim

00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:58.930
restaurant in San Francisco or you eat at
a good TexMex restaurant in Austin, or you

00:10:58.930 --> 00:11:04.759
eat
in a really cool, great fun environment in

00:11:04.759 --> 00:11:13.949
Miami, or you eat in Copa in Boston--the kitchens
are more diverse they are--the evolution

00:11:13.949 --> 00:11:17.410
is completely different now--I'm so happy
that that's happening.

00:11:17.410 --> 00:11:20.670
And I think America is one of the few places
that can create that.

00:11:20.670 --> 00:11:23.850
Because the entry
levels to work in a kitchen is still pretty

00:11:23.850 --> 00:11:28.240
low but you're curiosity level is very high
so people come from all walks of life which

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:29.240
is great.

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:32.769
I worked in the tech world but now I want
to become a chef.

00:11:32.769 --> 00:11:35.230
Look at what Nate's doing in Seattle.

00:11:35.230 --> 00:11:38.310
Look at what modern
cuisine is happening there.

00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:44.060
That will answer a lot of questions--not just
on the modern American cuisine today--but

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:49.060
those guys are
so bright so they'll probably figure out--maybe

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:55.149
how, maybe they have the question to end famine?

00:11:55.149 --> 00:12:00.019
You know because that's how that
modern cuisine is part of what they're working

00:12:00.019 --> 00:12:03.889
on and they're also working on these other
things and that's so great where cooks

00:12:03.889 --> 00:12:08.260
are coming into this industry not just on
the --the way I got in--that's one way--but

00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:12.399
it's so great to have people like Nate and
other people in the conversation because they're

00:12:12.399 --> 00:12:17.680
going to ask themselves questions: "How can
we figure out better against diabetes?

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:23.149
Allergies?" and these big questions that we
have that I've find it is important as a chef--we

00:12:23.149 --> 00:12:24.160
have to.

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:26.930
Filling restaurants, that's
part of our job and we should be doing this

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:30.630
especially if you have a big platform, you
should be doing that.

00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:34.742
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: But driving the larger conversation
about food and how things--

00:12:34.742 --> 00:12:35.742
&gt;&gt;Marcus: The larger conversation, absolutely.

00:12:35.742 --> 00:12:38.790
And that's what we do, I --my company--I'm
committed to that and that is why we have

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:43.790
community arm that is very strong and we do
cooking classes for free in the community.

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:46.139
That's why we have a tech side that is very
strong.

00:12:46.139 --> 00:12:47.620
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Tell us about the tech side.

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:48.620
What are you doing?

00:12:48.620 --> 00:12:56.680
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well I just felt with MS.com and
FoodRepublic.com--I wanted--what I saw online

00:12:56.680 --> 00:13:01.379
didn't sort of match with--the food
conversation I saw online didn't necessarily

00:13:01.379 --> 00:13:05.720
match with how-why I got into the industry.

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:10.230
I got into the industry about curiosity
and I went to learn.

00:13:10.230 --> 00:13:11.660
So I thought what an opportunity.

00:13:11.660 --> 00:13:16.860
What if Food Republic was focused on making
a food platform that was geared

00:13:16.860 --> 00:13:21.779
towards men--so it's about forty-five/fifty
five percent men/women--that is women friendly

00:13:21.779 --> 00:13:27.460
but that you learned something and we
celebrate each other as chefs so that was

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:30.810
a space that was open so we built a platform
around it.

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:35.100
On MS.com its about
seventy-thirty women to men and there we might

00:13:35.100 --> 00:13:40.490
focus on--it's very community oriented to
Harlem--its sort of a map into Harlem but

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:46.630
also what food healthy after yoga or after
you've been working out.

00:13:46.630 --> 00:13:54.379
So this adding something to the web space
was about learning and

00:13:54.379 --> 00:13:58.569
feeding people's curiosity and become better
cooks and become smarter shoppers in today's

00:13:58.569 --> 00:13:59.569
food space.

00:13:59.569 --> 00:14:00.569
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Yeah.

00:14:00.569 --> 00:14:02.689
Well it's interesting that you're using the
platform that you've been given or that you've

00:14:02.689 --> 00:14:06.629
really created for
yourself between things like Top Chef and

00:14:06.629 --> 00:14:10.589
your James Beard Awards and all the rest of
it to really become an activist in the food

00:14:10.589 --> 00:14:14.790
movement and maybe people don't know that
much about that, so it's interesting that

00:14:14.790 --> 00:14:16.240
you're--I mean it's great that you're doing
that.

00:14:16.240 --> 00:14:20.459
&gt;&gt;Marcus: I mean you have to I mean like these
wonderful platforms that you guys are part

00:14:20.459 --> 00:14:24.649
of creating--evolving are there for us
as consumers right, so when I opened Red Rooster

00:14:24.649 --> 00:14:29.870
and I had doubts I went to Twitter right away
and I was like "Should I have

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:34.149
vintage plates or new plates?" and right away-shoosh-
vintage comes in right?

00:14:34.149 --> 00:14:38.680
"Should I do my Jamaican oxtail or Grandma's
oxtail?"

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:39.680
--whoosh--right away.

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:45.649
[interviewer laughs] It's a fun way of engaging
and allowing people all over the world to

00:14:45.649 --> 00:14:51.069
participate and
feeling close to this narrative--this conversation.

00:14:51.069 --> 00:14:56.060
It's not about self-promotion, that's getting
tired, so I use Twitter as a--I

00:14:56.060 --> 00:15:03.019
curate carefully about the food conversation
