00:15:10.329 --> 00:15:11.360
somewhere else right?

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:14.561
But I know that the people there hang out
with me online, they want

00:15:14.561 --> 00:15:18.249
to be part of that, so I think have to curate--I
can't just post anything, you know?

00:15:18.249 --> 00:15:19.249
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Observation--

00:15:19.249 --> 00:15:24.910
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Observation, sifting and making
a yummy, sticky space for the people that

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:26.050
want to engage.

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:30.850
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: It's interesting how you've
used social media to influence the evolution

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:31.850
of Red Rooster.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:33.470
I think that's very
unusual, because I think chefs come in and

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:37.720
they have such a clear idea of what they want
to do and the personalities of the chefs

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:43.360
that I have met tend to be very controlling
for the most part, not in a bad way, so it's

00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:46.199
amazing that you've been able to engage in
that dialog and actually have it influence

00:15:46.199 --> 00:15:48.889
your menu and influence the choices that you're
making in a really--

00:15:48.889 --> 00:15:52.069
&gt;&gt;Marcus: For me it was Red Rooster and I
didn't grow up in Harlem so I can't say that

00:15:52.069 --> 00:15:55.810
I grew up there, but I wanted to create a
restaurant that was a mirror image food wise

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:57.350
of that community.

00:15:57.350 --> 00:16:01.589
And some people, depending on where you live,
where you grew up,

00:16:01.589 --> 00:16:07.170
know more or less about that community, it's
mystique, it's an old neighborhood, but maybe

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:11.139
everyone doesn't know about what it
really is and I thought, "Well, I've lived

00:16:11.139 --> 00:16:15.990
there for ten years, I want to map that out
on a menu.

00:16:15.990 --> 00:16:19.110
I want you to taste Harlem."

00:16:19.110 --> 00:16:26.399
Well there's obviously a center of African-American
heritage there that we should honor.

00:16:26.399 --> 00:16:31.309
There's also el barrio and on top of el
barrio there's a new Mexican community, therefore

00:16:31.309 --> 00:16:33.220
the tacquitos.

00:16:33.220 --> 00:16:38.029
There's also the Italian corridor, like it's
been there forever,

00:16:38.029 --> 00:16:44.550
and then you have this new West African because--yes,
there are Black African Americans, but the

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:49.990
West Africans has another new
ingredient that we might not know about so

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:53.920
that's why we have shrimp powder on the restaurant,
on the menu.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:58.509
So when you read the
menu of Red Rooster, it's curated and crafted

00:16:58.509 --> 00:17:02.540
based on seasonality, but also based on Harlem.

00:17:02.540 --> 00:17:06.650
You see Harlem and that's our job
there.

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:08.930
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That's amazing.

00:17:08.930 --> 00:17:12.990
In the--getting back to the book quickly,
you were pretty much an open book through

00:17:12.990 --> 00:17:17.240
out the process
and really went raw and told a lot of details,

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:18.540
very personal, deeply personal things.

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:21.070
I think if you're going to right a book like
that obviously you need to be prepared to

00:17:21.070 --> 00:17:22.070
do that.

00:17:22.070 --> 00:17:24.830
Was there anything you wish you had left out,
or a story that you actually wish

00:17:24.830 --> 00:17:25.980
you had included?

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:31.550
&gt;&gt;Marcus: I mean, the process of writing this
book was over five years, three days a week,

00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:36.590
I just woke up really early and wrote to
my editor and co-writer, Veronica.

00:17:36.590 --> 00:17:40.220
And I mean, we had to narrow it down to three
hundred something pages, from like fifteen

00:17:40.220 --> 00:17:42.660
hundred pages--something like that.

00:17:42.660 --> 00:17:48.060
But, there's a lot of stories, a lot of moments
obviously that didn’t' get in there, but

00:17:48.060 --> 00:17:50.590
you
know this book, like anything, was bad for

00:17:50.590 --> 00:17:52.100
a long time before it got good.

00:17:52.100 --> 00:17:55.180
So there was a lot of stuff out there and
how does this stuff--you

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:59.240
know--that's where Andy came in and really
edited this well.

00:17:59.240 --> 00:18:01.310
And, how do I tell these stories?

00:18:01.310 --> 00:18:06.510
I felt it like it was really about being
honest and not protecting--I knew when I walked

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:10.750
in I didn't want to do a victory lap.

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.680
It's so male and so tired.

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:16.370
[interviewer chuckles]
And I knew also that I wanted --if I'm going

00:18:16.370 --> 00:18:20.680
to borrow time from the reader--borrow that
time--there's a lot of stuff they can

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:23.670
do--they needed to get to know me better.

00:18:23.670 --> 00:18:29.680
Like I've read books about known people that
you know less about them after spent, like

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:33.230
for me, two weeks, 'cause I read slow and
I'm pissed after that.

00:18:33.230 --> 00:18:38.070
[laughter]
You have to get to know me better than before,

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:39.070
right?

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:40.820
And also, learn something about yourself.

00:18:40.820 --> 00:18:45.740
I want this book to be a sense of a
mirror to yourself like "You know what, what

00:18:45.740 --> 00:18:48.230
are we doing in that space?

00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:50.110
Are we hiring from this community?"

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:53.020
Well there's a
project right across the street here, how

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:56.420
many of those people work for Google?

00:18:56.420 --> 00:18:58.960
Like questions, questions, questions.

00:18:58.960 --> 00:19:00.110
What can we
do about that?

00:19:00.110 --> 00:19:02.750
How can we engage in that community?

00:19:02.750 --> 00:19:05.930
What responsibility do we have when we buy
these buildings?

00:19:05.930 --> 00:19:06.930
Who that great for?

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.440
It's great for a lot of people, could be greater
for even more.

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:10.590
What can we do to engage?

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:11.590
Questions.

00:19:11.590 --> 00:19:12.870
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: You know you're absolutely
right.

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:14.500
You raised some good questions.

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:15.500
I'd--

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:16.500
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Mmm hmm.

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:17.500
That's why we should hang out and have a beer
together.[Marcus laughs]

00:19:17.500 --> 00:19:19.060
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Let's hang out anytime you
want.

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:20.060
I'm on it.

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:21.060
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Yeah.

00:19:21.060 --> 00:19:22.060
yeah.

00:19:22.060 --> 00:19:23.060
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: I'll see you tomorrow.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:26.840
[laughter] One of the things that you talk
about in the book is the failure of Merkato

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:28.470
55
which I actually had the pleasure of dining

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:32.790
at before it opened; that makes me sound like
an insider--it was for an event that you

00:19:32.790 --> 00:19:40.060
were doing and I had the honor of dining at
your restaurant before it closed and you kind

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:43.240
of highlighted that as one of your
biggest professional disappointments.

00:19:43.240 --> 00:19:49.180
It was quickly followed by, well in the book
it was quickly followed by Top Chef Masters,

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:50.620
cooking for the White House state dinner.

00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:57.060
I'm curious what that failure taught you,
what the failure of Merkato 55 brought

00:19:57.060 --> 00:19:58.060
out of you?

00:19:58.060 --> 00:20:02.750
&gt;&gt;Marcus: It taught me a lot, I mean, there's
no way Rooster would have been as delicious

00:20:02.750 --> 00:20:05.830
and yummy without that failure, right?

00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:08.110
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Why do you say that?

00:20:08.110 --> 00:20:10.750
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well, because you learn so much.

00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:12.000
You guys learn so much.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.250
You guys launch products all the time--

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:15.250
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: That fail.

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:20.310
&gt;&gt;Marcus: That fails miserably and these are
the smartest and the brightest, but I know

00:20:20.310 --> 00:20:23.410
that you guys are sitting in war rooms and
saying "Why did it fail?

00:20:23.410 --> 00:20:24.410
It can't fail.

00:20:24.410 --> 00:20:27.250
We gotta do better," and you come back at
it right?

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:35.810
And-- so I think for me I learned about
the conversation about African fine dining

00:20:35.810 --> 00:20:36.810
is not wrong.

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:38.110
That is not wrong.

00:20:38.110 --> 00:20:41.500
I should have learned more about the community.

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:43.920
When
you're in the meat packing, there's nobody

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:49.660
would walk there on a Thursday at nine-thirty
that wants to have a Kumbaya African

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:50.660
experience.

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:55.240
They want to stand on a table, do shots, and
have a good ass time.

00:20:55.240 --> 00:20:58.840
Well let them have it, but it should not be
African

00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:03.780
good food, shouldn't be dragged down to that
misery.

00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:08.660
And shame on me for thinking that they were
even on the same conversation.

00:21:08.660 --> 00:21:11.060
I
think that is great that all that stuff is

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:15.200
there, and it has that incredible bridge and
tunnel feel,

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:17.851
[laughter]
which a bridge and tunnel should have, and

00:21:17.851 --> 00:21:19.131
that has nothing to do with {unintelligible}.

00:21:19.131 --> 00:21:23.080
I should have kept the two out of the way.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:25.630
So that's the quick answer right?

00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:29.910
What else did it teach about myself?

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:33.030
You know it was 2006 when we signed the lease
and when

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:38.710
you're in this bubble of bigger, better, bigger,
better, you know that lease was, that rent

00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:42.630
was about a hundred thousand dollars a month
for a

00:21:42.630 --> 00:21:43.630
restaurant,

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:44.630
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Wow.

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:47.120
&gt;&gt;Marcus: And we--I so wanted the deal I was
like "no problem, we'll just pack it."

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:49.820
You know and then you become chasing rent,
so

00:21:49.820 --> 00:21:53.770
that informed my decision about doing something
that I would not be chasing--commit is still

00:21:53.770 --> 00:21:56.150
to chase flavor, not to chasing rent.

00:21:56.150 --> 00:21:59.160
It taught me so many things.

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:03.720
Again, the purity of the product wasn't wrong,
it was my head wasn't clear and I wanted to

00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:08.620
do it too
bad so two things was good about it: we quit

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:16.760
before it got bad bad, and I learned on how
to listen and walk a neighborhood more.

00:22:16.760 --> 00:22:19.700
And
that's why I walked around Harlem before I

00:22:19.700 --> 00:22:20.700
engaged.

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:28.120
So hindsight, it all worked out, but it took
me a lot of self--sort of learning and so

00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:29.890
it's like okay.

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:31.480
And it's good, it's good.

00:22:31.480 --> 00:22:37.440
You get humbled and you listen and you get
better, or you don't and then there's another

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:38.920
path.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:47.200
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Well, in the book you bring
a lot of tastes so much to life, I'm wondering

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:51.730
if there's a cookbook in the works
for "Yes, Chef" like a journey of Chef Samuelsson?

00:22:51.730 --> 00:23:00.400
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Yeah, I mean, a lot of people have
asked and actually---maybe it's called "No,

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:01.400
Chef" I don't know.

00:23:01.400 --> 00:23:02.400
[Marcus and audience laugh]

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:04.650
I don't know.

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:10.100
We thought--I struggle with this a lot--but
I've never done anything where there wasn't

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:11.100
food.

00:23:11.100 --> 00:23:12.890
I'm like, I know this is a
memoir but how many recipes can we--are we

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:14.180
going to have?

00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:15.920
And Andy's like, "None."

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:17.490
My editor said, "None."

00:23:17.490 --> 00:23:19.450
I was like, "Whoa!"

00:23:19.450 --> 00:23:22.500
I
was nervous about how to engage with an audience

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:27.231
without food, and not stand on it in anyway.

00:23:27.231 --> 00:23:29.860
Even when I speak, I always bring up
food terms.

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:36.120
So that was a first for me, and I think--I
don't even think about what's next in terms

00:23:36.120 --> 00:23:38.980
of writing things in terms of
"Yes, Chef" right now, because I feel like

00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:41.110
we're in the middle of it.

00:23:41.110 --> 00:23:46.250
It's been a great run, and we have now, it's
sort of the

00:23:46.250 --> 00:23:48.640
product of what comes out of it, I don't know.

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:49.640
We'll see.

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:50.640
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Okay.

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:51.730
&gt;&gt;Marcus: But it's a interesting idea, yes--chef.

00:23:51.730 --> 00:23:54.400
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: All right, we'll take a percentage.

