&gt;&gt;Interviewer: --leading up to this event
I'm sure about [Marcus laughs] building--

00:24:01.463 --> 00:24:03.790
&gt;&gt;Marcus: I love that!

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:08.060
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: About building your brand and
sort of the empire that is Marcus Samuelsson.

00:24:08.060 --> 00:24:11.910
Can you talk to us a little bit about
the brand of Marcus Samuelsson and the pressure

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:14.690
of that and sort of how that's all going and
what's--

00:24:14.690 --> 00:24:20.010
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well I don't think any of it--I
get annoyed when you're a known person with

00:24:20.010 --> 00:24:24.130
a platform and you talk about the pressure.

00:24:24.130 --> 00:24:26.480
Pressure is being outside looking in.

00:24:26.480 --> 00:24:29.950
Pressure is "How am I going to pay my rent?"

00:24:29.950 --> 00:24:30.950
That's pressure.

00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:32.990
"How am I going to provide for
my family?"

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:36.620
Anyone with a platform and has an option on
what to do and how to curate a grade--lucky.

00:24:36.620 --> 00:24:38.100
You're lucky.

00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:43.070
And you're privileged and
that's what my sort of obsession with curation

00:24:43.070 --> 00:24:46.250
for the audience is, right?

00:24:46.250 --> 00:24:49.850
Because I know if we don't take care of that,
lights

00:24:49.850 --> 00:24:50.850
out.

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:52.020
Very quickly.

00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:55.280
So I wouldn't--I never look at it as pressure.

00:24:55.280 --> 00:25:00.630
I look at it as we have to be gooder than
the rest, there has to

00:25:00.630 --> 00:25:09.190
be narrative because the people that take
time out and spend money with us deserve it.

00:25:09.190 --> 00:25:14.840
And I think about everything that we touch
on that level.

00:25:14.840 --> 00:25:18.490
And it has to be--it can never be a false
promise.

00:25:18.490 --> 00:25:23.020
And if we're a two dollar cornbread, it should
feel like a

00:25:23.020 --> 00:25:24.300
twenty-eight dollar cornbread.

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:25.800
And the reality is--

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:26.800
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: There's twenty-eight dollar
cornbread?

00:25:26.800 --> 00:25:27.800
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Well--

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:28.800
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Where are you eating?

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:29.800
Where--

00:25:29.800 --> 00:25:30.800
&gt;&gt;Marcus: Truffles, truffles.

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:32.310
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: [laughs] Fair enough.

00:25:32.310 --> 00:25:38.310
&gt;&gt;Marcus: The reality is that I live in a
community where most of those great, grand

00:25:38.310 --> 00:25:42.770
experiences and amenities are south of that
community.

00:25:42.770 --> 00:25:44.880
And I resent that.

00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:49.610
And I'm not going to walk around angry, walking
around--"This is wrong, this is wrong."

00:25:49.610 --> 00:25:51.090
That's not
gonna happen.

00:25:51.090 --> 00:25:53.760
I'm going to provide it in my community first.

00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:57.420
So when you do that trip, when you come with
that beautiful bag, that

00:25:57.420 --> 00:26:02.640
changes your narrative of uptown and commercialism
is very fast.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:06.340
It's now changed real estate, it's now changed
job progression, so

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:10.540
it'll happen and it can be cornbread at a
time.

00:26:10.540 --> 00:26:13.440
If it's curated; if it's done really sticky,
yummy delicious.

00:26:13.440 --> 00:26:14.440
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: And not twenty-eight dollars--

00:26:14.440 --> 00:26:16.390
&gt;&gt;Marcus: And that's what I think about.

00:26:16.390 --> 00:26:19.730
You think about the brand, well that's the
brand, right?

00:26:19.730 --> 00:26:26.370
It's aspirational; it's inclusive
versus exclusive; and of course it's easier

00:26:26.370 --> 00:26:31.060
when you're a Swedopian living in Harlem to
think about those because I have

00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:37.240
different--I think about my grandmother from
Sweden or my sisters and brothers in Africa,

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:39.140
they're in my conversation.

00:26:39.140 --> 00:26:42.810
And I think
about the chef that I grew up with, you know,

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:49.150
